attributes.title: Group identification and well-being
attributes.description: Examining if a higher level of a person´s identification with his/her sports team or exercise group is associated with higher subjective well-being

q2.value:
Main question and hypothesis 

-	The main question of this study:
o	Do people with different levels of identification with their sports team or exercise group differ in their subjective well-being? 

-	The main hypotheses tested in this study:
o	A higher level of a person´s identification with his/her sports team or exercise group is associated with higher satisfaction with life
o	A higher level of a person´s identification with his/her sports team or exercise group is associated with higher positive affect
o	A higher level of a person´s identification with his/her sports team or exercise group is associated with lower negative affect

q3.value: Observational Study - Data is collected from study subjects that are not randomly assigned to a treatment. This includes surveys, “natural experiments,” and regression discontinuity designs.

value: No blinding is involved in this study.

question.value:
-	The data will be collected in an online survey (estimated duration: 20 – 25 minutes) with the software Qualtrics (Qualtrics, 2019)
-	Survey language: English
-	design: cross-sectional
-	There are no experimental manipulations within the study and therefore no conditions participants will be assigned to

q8.value: Registration prior to creation of data

question.value:
-	Recruiting takes place via social media (i.e. Facebook, Reddit) and/or personal contacts
-	Independent of the number of participants who have completed the survey, the survey will be accessible for possible participants until April 30, 2020
-	Data will be excluded under the following conditions:
       o Age < 18 years
       o Subject has answered instructed response items (three in total) or quality item incorrectly 
       o Subject does not exercise in a team or group
       o Subject has missing values on one of the four scales (SWLS, SPANE, Identification-scale, Satisfaction-Scale) (--> every item has to be answered)

Compensation: 
       o No financial compensation is provided
       o Subjects have the opportunity to receive a personality profile of their Big Five traits based on their individual BFI-S Ratings (Soto & John, 2017)
       o Psychology or business psychology students (Ruhr-Universität Bochum) have the opportunity to receive partial course ECTS (European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System)

q11.value:
-	The sample size was calculated with R statistics using the R-package pwr (Champely et al., 2018) and the function pwr.f2.test.
-	The calculation was based on effect sizes of similar studies which examined team identification as a fan (and not as a member) and its association with psychological health/psychological well-being or with social well-being (see “Background and purpose”). Those studies determined small to medium effect sizes (i.e. r = .34 (Wann, 2006) and r = .19 (Wann et al., 2015)). 
-	Therefore, a small to medium effect size (f2= R²/(1-R²) = 0.1) was chosen for the sample size calculation. With a significance level of α=.05 and a power of .80, a sample size of at least 80 participants was recommended.
o	pwr.f2.test(u=1,v=NULL,f2=0.1,power=.8, sig.level=0.05)

question.value:
Key dependent variable(s) and how they will be measured

-	subjective well-being (separated in cognitive (life satisfaction) and affective wellbeing defined by Diener et al., 1985):
     o life satisfaction will be measured with “The satisfaction with life Scale”; SWLS (Diener et al., 1985) 
     o affective well-being will be measured with the “Scale of Positive and Negative Experience”; SPANE (Diener et al., 2010)
     --> I will calculate the total value (sum) for each, the positive (SPANE-P) and the negative (SPANE-N) dimension

-	strength of person’s identification with his/her sports team or exercise group will be measured with a four-item (Postmes et al., 2013) 
o	Items will be scored on a 7-point Likert-scale (1=fully disagree; 7=fully agree)


Other additional data collected

-	Demographic information: 
        o Gender
        o Age (in years)
        o Country 
        o Relationship status 

- Sport specific information: 
        o Sport practice (yes/no): does subject regularly practice any sport?
        o Sport mainly practiced: which sport does subject mainly practice (drop down list)
        o Month/years of sport participation (in reference to main sport)
        o Times and hours per week of sport participation (in reference to main sport)
        o Level of performance (main sport; 10-point Likert-scale (amateur athlete to professional athlete))
        o Type of Exercise (see above): in a sports team vs. exercise group vs. alone
        o Sport identity: whether a subject identify itself more as a team or individual athlete (subjective)
        o Other sports: does subject regularly does any other sports? (yes/no) --> If yes, then what other sports (text field) 
-	„Hierarchical (Multicomponent) Model of In-Group Identification“ (Leach et al., 2008)

Analyses

-	Statistical model: linear regression
-	I will use three simple linear regressions (standardized coefficients)
o Each between the strength of a person’s identification with his/her sports team or exercise group (as predictor) and…
               --> his/her satisfaction with life (as criterion)
               -->his/her positive affect (as criterion)
               -->his/her negative affect (as criterion)

q23.value:
1. Background and purpose

For humans the feeling of belonging to a group is very important (named as need to belong; (Baumeister & Leary, 1995). There is evidence, that to achieve a high level of psychological well-being, this feeling of belonging must be satisfied (Lavigne, Vallerand, & Crevier-Braud, 2011). Hence membership in and identification with a group seems to be important for one’s psychological and social health (Leach et al., 2008). Identification “refers to the individual member’s relationship to … [an] entity … [and is] … the positive emotional valuation of the relationship between self and ingroup” (Postmes, Haslam, & Jans, 2013, p. 599). This includes that a person has to be aware, that he or she belongs to this group (Ellemers, Kortekaas, & Ouwerkerk, 1999). 
However not every group has an equally strong influence on a person (Leach et al., 2008). Recent research points out that a higher level of identification with a group enhances psychological benefits and thus has a stronger positive influence (Wann, Waddill, Polk, & Weaver, 2011). In addition to other studies on certain group memberships and identification, (for an overview of examples see Wann, Waddill, Brasher, & Ladd, 2015) one can find a lot of studies about identification with a sport team as a fan or spectator (Wann, 2006; Wann et al., 2015; Wann & Polk, 2007), which indicate that higher team identification (as a fan) entails many psychological advantages. Examples that can be put forward are a higher self-esteem, more well-being, more pride and more self-confidence (Keaton & Honeycutt, 2014). Moreover, team identification (as a fan or spectator) is positively related to social well-being and the establishment and maintenance of social connections and relationships (Wann et al., 2011). Summing up it can be stated that identification with a sport team is associated to positive outcomes which may have a positive effect on a person’s subjective well-being. 
There are numerous definitions of subjective well-being. In the planned study, we refer to one of the most influential ones by Diener, Emmons, Larsen, and Griffin (1985) which differentiates between cognitive and affective components of well-being. Cognitive well-being is the positive evaluation of one’s life and thus considers a person's satisfaction with life (Diener et al., 1985). Affective well-being is characterized by the frequent occurrence of positive affect and the rare occurrence of negative affect (Rahm, Heise, & Schuldt, 2017). Currently there is no research which specifically examined a person´s identification with his/her sports team or exercise group as a member of the team and his/her subjective well-being. It should be mentioned that preliminary investigations in the study of Wann et al. (2015) point out that persons who were also a member of the team and not only a fan, appear to have higher levels of social relations and social wellbeing. Therefore, the purpose of this study is to examine if members of a sport team or exercise group (and not just fans or spectators) with different levels of identification with his or her sports team or exercise group differ in their subjective well-being.  

___________________________________________________________________________________________

2. Note regarding Coronavirus pandemic – Covid-19 

The massive impact of COVID-19 on our everyday life will most probably also have an effect on some constructs included in this study. The reason for that is that most people won’t be able to participate in regular sport activities the way they are used to because of  lockdowns in most countries (see Kaplan, Frias, & Mcfall-johnsen, 2020). Additionally, participant’s overall well-being might be lower. To take these possible differences into account, we will administer some questionnaires twice.
Questions on the frequency and duration of sport participation will be assessed for the current situation as well as retrospectively regarding the time before the coronavirus pandemic, if the participants indicate that their sport participation is affected due to the coronavirus pandemic.
The SWLS (Diener et al., 1985) will be assessed two times. First, at the beginning of the survey with regard to the subject’s current life satisfaction. Second, close to the end of the survey with regard to subjects’ life satisfaction before the corona crisis.
The SPANE (Diener et al., 2010) will be assessed two times: First, at the beginning of the survey with regard to the subject’s current life.  Second, close to the end of the survey in regard to the participants experiences and feelings during sport participation.
Questions:
-	Is the subject’s sport participation limited due to the corona pandemic? If yes, then:
     o How often (per week) the subject practiced his/her main sport prior the corona pandemic
     o How many hours (per week) the subject spends participating his/her main sport prior the pandemic

___________________________________________________________________________________________

3. Other information

-	I would like to state, that the data will be collected in collaboration with another researcher 
      o Due to that fact our survey will contain additional scales and items which are preregistered elsewhere and are not of interest for the presented study

___________________________________________________________________________________________

attributes.title: NBBA (NanoBit Biochemical Assay )
attributes.description: Original data for the paper title: "Development of a cell free split luciferase biochemical assay as a tool for screening for inhibitors of challenging protein-protein interaction targets"
tags: All the original files (CSV and PDF figures) for the paper have upload.
Each CSV file is titled with the figure number and letter to help the readers to link each data with the corresponding figure.

q3.value: Targeting the interaction of proteins with weak binding affinities or low solubility represents a particular challenge for drug screening. The NanoLuc Binary Technology (NanoBiT) was originally developed to detect protein-protein interactions in live mammalian cells. Here we report the successful translation of the NanoBit cellular assay into a biochemical, cell-free format using mammalian cell lysates. We show that the assay is suitable for the detection of both strong and weak protein interactions such as those involving the binding of RAS oncoproteins to either RAF or Phosphoinositide 3-kinase (PI3K) effectors respectively, and that it is also effective for the study of poorly soluble protein domains such as the RAS binding domain of PI3K. Furthermore, the RAS interaction assay is sensitive and responds to both strong and weak RAS inhibitors. Our data show that the assay is robust, reproducible, cost-effective, and can be adapted for small and large-scale screening approaches. The NanoBit Biochemical Assay offers an attractive tool for drug screening against challenging protein-protein interaction targets, including the interaction of RAS with PI3K.

registration_responses.q3: Targeting the interaction of proteins with weak binding affinities or low solubility represents a particular challenge for drug screening. The NanoLuc Binary Technology (NanoBiT) was originally developed to detect protein-protein interactions in live mammalian cells. Here we report the successful translation of the NanoBit cellular assay into a biochemical, cell-free format using mammalian cell lysates. We show that the assay is suitable for the detection of both strong and weak protein interactions such as those involving the binding of RAS oncoproteins to either RAF or Phosphoinositide 3-kinase (PI3K) effectors respectively, and that it is also effective for the study of poorly soluble protein domains such as the RAS binding domain of PI3K. Furthermore, the RAS interaction assay is sensitive and responds to both strong and weak RAS inhibitors. Our data show that the assay is robust, reproducible, cost-effective, and can be adapted for small and large-scale screening approaches. The NanoBit Biochemical Assay offers an attractive tool for drug screening against challenging protein-protein interaction targets, including the interaction of RAS with PI3K.
